                \n {"practice":"3","code":"SD-4","subCode":"d) using secure design patterns;","explanation":"Secure design patterns are reusable solutions to common security problems in ICS. They provide a structured approach to mitigate vulnerabilities during the design phase, ensuring robust and resilient systems.","context":"In industrial control systems, secure design patterns help address specific threats like unauthorized access, data integrity breaches, and denial of service by embedding security into the architecture.","challenges":["Legacy system integration: Older ICS components may not support modern secure design patterns, requiring costly upgrades or workarounds. Example: Retrofitting a PLC with secure authentication mechanisms.","Performance trade-offs: Security measures like encryption can impact real-time performance. Example: Adding TLS to SCADA communications may introduce latency.","Vendor lock-in: Proprietary systems may limit the implementation of standardized secure patterns. Example: A vendor-specific HMI may not allow custom secure configurations.","Complexity management: Layering multiple secure patterns can increase system complexity. Example: Combining zero-trust and defense-in-depth in a DCS environment.","Skill gaps: Teams may lack expertise in applying secure patterns to ICS. Example: Misconfiguring a secure boot pattern in an RTOS."],"best_practices":[{"description":"Implement the principle of least privilege in ICS design to minimize attack surfaces. Example: Restricting HMI access to only necessary functions for operators. Resource: Siemens' guide on secure HMI design (https://new.siemens.com/global/en/products/automation/industry-software/automation-software/tia-portal.html) details role-based access control aligned with SD-4.","url":" https://new.siemens.com/global/en/products/automation/industry-software/automation-software/tia-portal.html","url_description":"Siemens TIA Portal security features for ICS design"},{"description":"Ap