ure","url":"https://nvlpubs.nist.gov/nistpubs/ir/2021/NIST.IR.8183.pdf","description":"Framework for selecting security patterns in ICS"}]},{"id":"KA2","title":"Pattern Implementation Validation","description":"Defines verification processes to ensure secure patterns are correctly implemented without compromising ICS operational requirements. Includes testing for functional safety and performance impacts.","related_links":[{"title":"IEC 62443-4-1 Test Requirements","url":"https://www.iec.ch","description":"Standardized testing approach for secure implementations"},{"title":"Honeywell Secure Design Validation Guide","url":"https://www.honeywellprocess.com/library/support/Pages/security.aspx","description":"Vendor-specific implementation validation methods"}]},{"id":"KA3","title":"Pattern Documentation Standards","description":"Specifies requirements for documenting applied secure patterns, including rationale for selection and configuration details, to support maintenance and audits per SD-4.","related_links":[{"title":"ABB Secure Design Documentation Template","url":"https://new.abb.com/control-systems/system-800xa/operations/security","description":"Structured template for pattern documentation"},{"title":"ISA TR62443-4-1 Documentation Guidelines","url":" https://www.isa.org/standards-and-publications/isa-standards/isa-62443-standards/","description":"Industry best practices for security documentation"}]},{"id":"KA4","title":"Pattern Maintenance Procedures","description":"Outlines processes for periodic review and updating of implemented secure patterns to address evolving threats and technology changes, fulfilling SD-4's maintenance requirement.","related_links":[{"title":"Siemens Security Patch Management Guide","url":"https://support.industry.siemens.com/cs/ww/en/view/109479173","description":"Vendor approach to maintaining secure designs"},{"title":"ICS-CERT Security Patch Management","url":"https://www.cisa.gov/resources-tools/services/ics-cert","description":"ICS-specific pattern update methodologies"}]}],"name":"Secure design best practices","description":"A process shall be employed to ensure that secure design best practices are documented and applied to the design process. These practices shall be periodically reviewed and updated. Secure design practices include but are not be limited to: d) using secure design patterns;","details":{"risk_assessment_and_threat_modeling":{"why":"To identify and mitigate potential security threats during the design phase.","methodologies":[{"name":"STRIDE","description":"A threat modeling methodology that categorizes threats into Spoofing, Tampering, Repudiation, Information Disclosure, Denial of Service, and Elevation of Privilege."},{"name":"ICS-specific threat models","description":"Custom threat models tailored for Industrial Control Systems to address unique operational and security requirements."}],"tools":[{"name":"Microsoft Threat Modeling Tool","purpose":"To create and analyze threat models using the STRIDE methodology."},{"name":"NIST 800-30 adapted for SCADA systems","purpose":"A risk assessment framework tailored for SCADA and ICS environments."}],"case_study":{"example":"A power plant implemented STRIDE-based threat modeling for its Distributed Control System (DCS), identifying critical vulnerabilities in communication protocols and mitigating them through secure design patterns."}},"audit_and_compliance_verification":{"why":"To ensure adherence to secure design best practices and IEC 62443-4-1 requirements.","audit_checklist":["Verify documentation of secure design patterns used in the design process.","Check for periodic reviews and updates of secure design practices.","Ensure that threat modeling results are incorporated into the design."],"metrics":[{"kpi":"Percentage of scoped requirements implemented","target":"100%"},{"kpi":"Number of design reviews conducted annually","target":"At least 2"}],"compliance_procedure":"Documentation of secure design patterns, threat modeling results, and review logs must be maintained and made available for audits."},"training_and_competency_requirements":{"why":"To ensure that personnel involved in the design process are knowledgeable about secure design practices.","training_programs":[{"name":"ISA/IEC 62443 Cybersecurity Fundamentals Specialist","description":"Certification covering fundamental concepts of ICS security, including secure design."},{"name":"GICSP (Global Industrial Cyber Security Professional)","description":"Certification focused on securing industrial control systems, including design best practices."}],"competency_assessment":"Annual competency reviews to ensure design engineers maintain up-to-date knowledge of secure design patterns and threat modeling techniques."},"tooling_and_automation_support":{"why":"To integrate secure design practices into the development lifecycle efficiently.","tools":[{"name":"Static Application Security Testing (SAST) tools","purpose":"To analyze source code for security vulnerabilities during the design phase."},{"name":"Dynamic Application Security Testing (DAST) tools","purpose":"To test running applications for security vulnerabilities."}],"automation_strategy":"Integrate SAST and DAST tools into the CI/CD pipeline to automatically scan for vulnerabilities during the design and development phases."},"handling_legacy_systems_and_constraints":{"why":"Legacy systems may not support modern secure design patterns, requiring alternative strategies.","strategies":[{"approach":"Network segmentation","description":"Isolate legacy components in separate network zones to limit exposure to threats."},{"approach":"Compensating controls","description":"Implement additional security measures such as intrusion detection systems (IDS) to monitor legacy systems."}],"example_policy":"A policy for integrating legacy PLCs into a modern ICS design includes network segmentation, regular vulnerability assessments, and compensating controls like IDS."},"stakeholder